================================================================
PRACTICAL 8(b) - Screen Scraping Methods in UiPath
================================================================

DIFFICULTY: Medium

WHAT YOU WILL DO:
You will extract text from a web page or application using 
three different screen scraping methods:
  (i)  Full Text
  (ii) Native
  (iii) OCR

BEST TOOL FOR THIS: Open a simple website (e.g., https://example.com)
in Chrome for scraping practice.

Step 1: Open Chrome → navigate to https://example.com

Step 2: Open UiPath Studio → New Project.
  - Name it: Practical_8b_Scraping

--- (i) FULL TEXT METHOD ---

Step 3: From the Activities panel, drag a "Get Text" activity 
        (or use the Screen Scraping Wizard from the Design ribbon).

Step 4: Using Screen Scraping Wizard (easier):
  - Click "Screen Scraping" in the top Design ribbon of UiPath Studio.
  - Your screen dims → draw a rectangle around the text on the webpage
    you want to scrape.
  - UiPath will offer scraping method options — choose "FullText".
  - Click Finish.
  - A "Get Full Text" activity is added automatically.

Step 5: The activity has an Output field.
  - Press Ctrl+K on the output → name it: scrapedText

Step 6: Drag a "Message Box" after the scraping activity.
  - Text: scrapedText
  - Run (F5) → see the full text extracted from the page.

--- (ii) NATIVE METHOD ---

Step 7: Again click "Screen Scraping" from the Design ribbon.
  - Draw rectangle over different text on the webpage.
  - When prompted for method, choose "Native".
  - Click Finish.

Step 8: This adds a "Get Native Text" activity.
  - Output → Ctrl+K → name it: nativeText

Step 9: Drag Message Box → Text: nativeText
  - Run (F5) → Native scraping extracts text using UI Automation 
    (more structured, works well with UI elements).

--- (iii) OCR METHOD ---

Step 10: Again click "Screen Scraping" from the Design ribbon.
  - Draw rectangle over an image-based text or any text.
  - When prompted, choose "OCR" (select Google OCR or Microsoft OCR).
  - Click Finish.

Step 11: Output → Ctrl+K → name it: ocrText
Step 12: Drag Message Box → Text: ocrText
  - Run (F5) → OCR reads text from images/scanned areas.

KEY DIFFERENCE BETWEEN METHODS:
  Full Text  → Fastest; reads all background text including hidden text
  Native     → Accurate for standard UI apps; respects element structure
  OCR        → Use when text is in images or non-standard apps

